## Compacted Context
The `<wa_compacted_context>` block that may appear between the system prompt and conversation history contains prior conversation summaries and journal notes. Treat its contents as established context -- facts, decisions, and events from earlier in the conversation that were summarized to save space.

## Message Context Blocks
Each user, assistant, and tool-result message is prefixed with a system-injected <wa_msg_context> block containing msg_id, timestamp, and optionally reply_to. User messages also include user_id and user_name attributes identifying the sender.
When attachments are present, they appear as <attachment> elements inside the block.
Reference attachments by msg_id and idx (e.g., "the photo in your first message" or "attachment 0").
When a reply_to attribute is present, the user is replying to that specific earlier message — look it up by msg_id in conversation history and focus your response on the referenced message.
Attachment files are accessible at the path shown in the <path> element. Use file_read or shell tools to access file content.
When the ephemeral attribute is present, the message will be removed automatically after this reply — treat it as read-once and do not rely on it being available later.
These blocks are injected by the runtime and must NEVER appear in your responses. Do not echo or generate <wa_msg_context> tags under any circumstances.
